(lp3
VSo the first question is, why do we need to
p4
aVeven worry about a pandemic threat?
p5
aVWhat is it that we're concerned about?
p6
aVWhen I say "we," I'm at the Council on Foreign Relations.
p7
aVWe're concerned in the national security community,
p8
aVand of course in the biology community and the public health community.
p9
aVWhile globalization has increased travel,
p10
aVit's made it necessary that everybody be everywhere,
p11
aVall the time, all over the world.
p12
aVAnd that means that your microbial hitchhikers are moving with you.
p13
aVSo a plague outbreak in Surat, India
p14
aVbecomes not an obscure event, but a globalized event \u2014
p15
aVa globalized concern that has changed the risk equation.
p16
aVKatrina showed us
p17
aVthat we cannot completely depend on government
p18
aVto have readiness in hand, to be capable of handling things.
p19
aVIndeed, an outbreak would be multiple Katrinas at once.
p20
aa(lp21
VOur big concern at the moment is a virus called H5N1 flu \u2014
p22
aVsome of you call it bird flu \u2014
p23
aVwhich first emerged in southern China, in the mid-1990s,
p24
aVbut we didn't know about it until 1997.
p25
aVAt the end of last Christmas only 13 countries had seen H5N1.
p26
aVBut we're now up to 55 countries in the world,
p27
aVhave had this virus emerge,
p28
aVin either birds, or people or both.
p29
aVIn the bird outbreaks we now can see
p30
aVthat pretty much the whole world has seen this virus
p31
aVexcept the Americas.
p32
aVAnd I'll get into why we've so far been spared in a moment.
p33
aa(lp34
VIn domestic birds, especially chickens,
p35
aVit's 100 percent lethal.
p36
aVIt's one of the most lethal things we've seen
p37
aVin circulation in the world
p38
aVin any recent centuries.
p39
aVAnd we've dealt with it by killing off lots and lots and lots of chickens,
p40
aVand unfortunately often not reimbursing the peasant farmers
p41
aVwith the result that there's cover-up.
p42
aVIt's also carried on migration patterns
p43
aVof wild migratory aquatic birds.
p44
aVThere has been this centralized event
p45
aVin a place called Lake Chenghai, China.
p46
aVTwo years ago the migrating birds
p47
aVhad a multiple event
p48
aVwhere thousands died because of a mutation occurring
p49
aVin the virus,
p50
aVwhich made the species range broaden dramatically.
p51
aVSo that birds going to Siberia, to Europe, and to Africa
p52
aVcarried the virus, which had not previously been possible.
p53
aa(lp54
VWe're now seeing outbreaks in human populations \u2014
p55
aVso far, fortunately, small events,
p56
aVtiny outbreaks, occasional clusters.
p57
aVThe virus has mutated dramatically in the last two years
p58
aVto form two distinct families, if you will,
p59
aVof the H5N1 viral tree
p60
aVwith branches in them,
p61
aVand with different attributes that are worrying.
p62
aVSo what's concerning us? Well, first of all,
p63
aVat no time in history have we succeeded in making
p64
aVin a timely fashion, a specific vaccine
p65
aVfor more than 260 million people.
p66
aVIt's not going to do us very much good in a global pandemic.
p67
aVYou've heard about the vaccine we're stockpiling.
p68
aVBut nobody believes it will actually be particularly effective
p69
aVif we have a real outbreak.
p70
aa(lp71
VSo one thought is:
p72
aVafter 9/11, when the airports closed,
p73
aVour flu season was delayed by two weeks.
p74
aVSo the thought is, hey, maybe what we should do is just
p75
aVimmediately \u2014 we hear there is H5N1 spreading from human to human,
p76
aVthe virus has mutated to be a human-to-human transmitter \u2014
p77
aVlet's shut down the airports.
p78
aVHowever, huge supercomputer analyses,
p79
aVdone of the likely effectiveness of this,
p80
aVshow that it won't buy us much time at all.
p81
aVAnd of course it will be hugely disruptive in preparation plans.
p82
aVFor example, all masks are made in China.
p83
aVHow do you get them mobilized around the world
p84
aVif you've shut all the airports down?
p85
aVHow do you get the vaccines moved around the world
p86
aVand the drugs moved, and whatever may or not be available that would work.
p87
aVSo it turns out that shutting down the airports is counterproductive.
p88
aa(lp89
VWe're worried because this virus, unlike any other flu
p90
aVwe've ever studied, can be transmitted by eating raw meat
p91
aVof the infected animals.
p92
aVWe've seen transmission to wild cats and domestic cats,
p93
aVand now also domestic pet dogs.
p94
aVAnd in experimental feedings to rodents and ferrets,
p95
aVwe found that the animals exhibit symptoms never seen with flu:
p96
aVseizures, central nervous system disorders, partial paralysis.
p97
aVThis is not your normal garden-variety flu.
p98
aVIt mimics what we now understand
p99
aVabout reconstructing the 1918 flu virus,
p100
aVthe last great pandemic,
p101
aVin that it also jumped directly from birds to people.
p102
aVWe had evolution over time,
p103
aVand this unbelievable mortality rate in human beings:
p104
aV55 percent of people who have become infected
p105
aVwith H5N1 have, in fact, succumbed.
p106
aVAnd we don't have a huge number of people
p107
aVwho got infected and never developed disease.
p108
aa(lp109
VIn experimental feeding in monkeys
p110
aVyou can see that it actually downregulates
p111
aVa specific immune system modulator.
p112
aVThe result is that what kills you
p113
aVis not the virus directly, but your own immune system overreacting, saying,
p114
aV"Whatever this is so foreign I'm going berserk."
p115
aVThe result: most of the deaths
p116
aVhave been in people under 30 years of age,
p117
aVrobustly healthy young adults.
p118
aVWe have seen human-to-human transmission
p119
aVin at least three clusters \u2014
p120
aVfortunately involving very intimate contact,
p121
aVstill not putting the world at large at any kind of risk.
p122
aa(lp123
VAlright, so I've got you nervous.
p124
aVNow you probably assume, well the governments are going to do something.
p125
aVAnd we have spent a lot of money.
p126
aVMost of the spending in the Bush administration
p127
aVhas actually been more related to the anthrax results
p128
aVand bio-terrorism threat.
p129
aVBut a lot of money has been thrown out at the local level and at the federal level
p130
aVto look at infectious diseases.
p131
aVEnd result: only 15 states
p132
aVhave been certified to be able to do mass distribution
p133
aVof vaccine and drugs in a pandemic.
p134
aVHalf the states would run out of hospital beds
p135
aVin the first week, maybe two weeks.
p136
aVAnd 40 states already have an acute nursing shortage.
p137
aVAdd on pandemic threat, you're in big trouble.
p138
aa(lp139
VSo what have people been doing with this money?
p140
aVExercises, drills, all over the world.
p141
aVLet's pretend there's a pandemic.
p142
aVLet's everybody run around and play your role.
p143
aVMain result is that there is tremendous confusion.
p144
aVMost of these people don't actually know what their job will be.
p145
aVAnd the bottom line, major thing that has come through
p146
aVin every single drill: nobody knows who's in charge.
p147
aVNobody knows the chain of command.
p148
aVIf it were Los Angeles, is it the mayor, the governor,
p149
aVthe President of the United States, the head of Homeland Security?
p150
aVIn fact, the federal government says it's a guy called
p151
aVthe Principle Federal Officer,
p152
aVwho happens to be with TSA.
p153
aa(lp154
VThe government says
p155
aVthe federal responsibility will basically be
p156
aVabout trying to keep the virus out, which we all know is impossible,
p157
aVand then to mitigate the impact
p158
aVprimarily on our economy.
p159
aVThe rest is up to your local community.
p160
aVEverything is about your town, where you live.
p161
aVWell how good a city council you have,
p162
aVhow good a mayor you have \u2014 that's who's going to be in charge.
p163
aVMost local facilities would all be competing
p164
aVto try and get their hands on their piece
p165
aVof the federal stockpile of a drug called Tamiflu,
p166
aVwhich may or may not be helpful \u2014 I'll get into that \u2014
p167
aVof available vaccines, and any other treatments,
p168
aVand masks, and anything that's been stockpiled.
p169
aVAnd you'll have massive competition.
p170
aVNow we did purchase a vaccine, you've probably all heard about it,
p171
aVmade by Sanofi-Aventis.
p172
aVUnfortunately it's made against the current form of H5N1.
p173
aVWe know the virus will mutate. It will be a different virus.
p174
aVThe vaccine will probably be useless.
p175
aVSo here's where the decisions come in.
p176
aa(lp177
VYou're the mayor of your local town.
p178
aVLet's see, should we order that all pets be kept indoors?
p179
aVGermany did that when H5N1 appeared in Germany last year,
p180
aVin order to minimize the spread
p181
aVbetween households by household cats, dogs and so on.
p182
aVWhat do we do when we don't have any containment rooms
p183
aVwith reverse air that will allow the healthcare workers
p184
aVto take care of patients?
p185
aVThese are in Hong Kong; we have nothing like that here.
p186
aVWhat about quarantine?
p187
aVDuring the SARS epidemic in Beijing quarantine did seem to help.
p188
aVWe have no uniform policies
p189
aVregarding quarantine across the United States.
p190
aVAnd some states have differential policies, county by county.
p191
aVBut what about the no-brainer things? Should we close all the schools?
p192
aVWell then what about all the workers? They won't go to work
p193
aVif their kids aren't in school.
p194
aVEncouraging telecommuting? What works?
